title: Bad Typo
message:
Bad Typo

"Abgehackt" actually means "cut something off" while "abgehakt" (note the missing c) means "check off". "Abhaken" refers to "Haken" which means "check mark" (in this context). It is a common issue in Germany that people get this wrong in their orthography.

title: Bugfix break / streak calculation around DST change dates
message:
Bugfix break / streak calculation around DST change dates

Due to daylight saving time (DST), there is one day with 23 hours and one with 25 hours once a year.
This leads to incorrect results when calculation the number of days by just dividing the millis difference
by 24 hours. Example (German time zone): one tick on 24 Mar 17 and one on 27 Mar 17 gave a break of
1 day instead of 2; one tick on 26 Mar 17 and one on 27 Mar 17 gave a streak of 1 instead of 2. This
bugfix corrects the breaks / streaks calculation for time spans including the DST change moment.

title: Time info code cleanup
message:
Time info code cleanup

Time info is saved to the database for ticks on the current day but not used in the program
anywhere. On the contrary, all calendar operations rely on the fact that the time info is
cleared. This can be simplified by not loading the time info from the database in the first place.
This allows to remove the instructions clearing the hour, minutes, seconds, and milliseconds
scattered all over the code.

title: Fix year for weeks at turn of the year
message:
Fix year for weeks at turn of the year

The year number for weeks at the turn of the year changes within the week,
which lead to incorrect binning of the year-week-combination when calculating
the weekly distribution. This is corrected by this bug fix.

title: Fix trend indicator angle calculation
message: Fix trend indicator angle calculation

title: Trend indicator switchable in summary view
message:
Trend indicator switchable in summary view

Tapping the trend indicator will cycle through all possible trend ranges. Initial range is taken from settings.
The angle of each range's trend indicator arrow is scaled to the biggest possible value for a single tick track,
the largest possible trend value (slope) corresponds to a vertical arrow.
Trend indicators for multi tick tracks are scaled the same way and capped at these maximum values.

title: Trend indicator
message:
Trend indicator

Replace the now redundant "Days since last" summary number (days since last can
now be read off the new streaks/breaks chart) by a trend indicator. The trend
is computed as the slope of a linear least square fit calculated over the ticks
of the track within the specified trend range. The trend range can be selected
in the settings (default 2 weeks). No trend indicator will be available if the
trend range reaches back further than the first tick was recorded for that track.
In this case, a '?' will be displayed. Otherwise a tilted arrow shows the trend,
wheras a 45° maximum increasing/decreasing trend will be displayed as a vertical
arrow pointing straight upwards/downwards. Larger trend values are symbolized by
a dashed upwards/downwards arrow to visualized the capping at 45°.
The current day is included in the trend calculation, no matter if it's early or
late on this day.

Refactoring of SummaryNumber to replace hard-coded distances by generic ones
based on font properties. Adjust 'show track' layout to make all summary number
widgets exactly the same size.

title: Time info hotfix and SummaryGraph bugfix
message:
Time info hotfix and SummaryGraph bugfix

 Commit f1bc4ed added the missing time info for active day multi ticks and made sure to only save the
 time info for active day single ticks (and not for single ticks for past days). (NB: the first part of my commit
 message of f1bc4ed was not accurate about this).
 As a result of these changes an existing code error in the calculation of the number of days between two
 dates became apparent: the number of days between two dates cannot be calculated by just dividing the
 time difference in ms by the number of ms per day as it can be more or less than 24 hrs for two days in
 a row with time info attached.
 This hotfix removes the time info from the dates before day difference calculation. It's rather ugly and will
 be replaced by a nicer solution later.

 The change in SummaryGraph fixes a bug introduced with b855ba7 that prevents empty streaks and
 weekday graphs from being shown.

title: Show pauses in streaks chart

Show pauses in streaks chart

The streaks chart is converted to a streaks/pauses chart with streak peaks showing
upward and pause peaks showing downward. This neatly corresponds to the longest
streak / longest pause indicators to the right of the chart.

Code cleanup of SummaryGraph and moderate refactor of onDraw. Generic distances between
curve/axis/markers and labels based on fontMetrics instead of hard coded values.

Streak calculation code cleanup and streamline.

title: Fix longest streak calculation for single day activities
message:
Fix longest streak calculation for single day activities

If an activity is done on say two, three, four and so on days in a row,
then the longest streak is 2, 3, 4 and so on (correct). If an activity is
done on just one day and then paused, then the longest streak is
currently 0 (same as if no activity at all has ever been done). Based on
the above reasoning it appears more logical to calculate the streak
duration as 1 in this case.

title: Fix longest break duration
message:
Fix longest break duration

If you do an activity say on Monday and on Wednesday, then there is a break
of one day where you didn't do that activity (longest break = 1 day). Hence
if you do an activity on two consecutive days, then there is no break at all
(longest break = 0 days). Currently Tickmate shows 2 and 1 days, respectively,
in the above cases. This is going to be fixed by this commit.

title: Correcting weekly mean calculation
message:
Correcting weekly mean calculation

Currently the weekly mean is calculated by (number of ticks / number of weeks), but depending on the current weekday and the weekday when the track began, it will add up to 6 value-zero elements to the mean calculations.

This is corrected by instead calculating the mean by (number of ticks / number of days) * 7.0, which is independent of the current and starting weekday.
